 <refnamediv>
  <refname>&progcmd;</refname>
  <refpurpose>
   The &progname; is a tool to manage meta-information within DocBook5 documents.
  </refpurpose>
 </refnamediv>
 <refsynopsisdiv id="docmanager.synopsis">
  <title>Synopsis</title>
  <cmdsynopsis>
   <command>&progcmd;</command>
   <arg choice="opt">-h</arg>
   <arg choice="plain" rep="repeat">-f FILES</arg>
   <group choice="req">
    <arg>-s SET</arg>
    <arg>-g GET</arg>
    <arg>-a ANALYZE</arg>
   </group>
   <!--<arg choice="plain">[-h] -f FILES [FILES ...] (-s SET [SET ...] | -g GET [GET ...] | -a ANALYZE [ANALYZE ...])</arg>-->
  </cmdsynopsis>
 </refsynopsisdiv>
 <refsect1 id="docmanager.description">
  <title>Description</title>
  <para>
   The &progname; is a tool to manage meta-information within DocBook5 documents. It
   is possible to add new information as well as editing and deleting. The main advantage
   of this tool is the analyze feature. This feature creates a table with all wanted
   information. You can restrict the information with a lightweight SQL syntax.
  </para>
 </refsect1>
 <refsect1 id="docmanager.optionaloptions">
  <title>Optional Options</title>
  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><option>-h</option> or <option>--help</option></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Shows this help message and exit.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
 </refsect1>
 <refsect1 id="docmanager.options">
  <title>Options</title>
  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><option>-a</option> or <option>--analyze</option></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Similar to get, but query can be given as pseudo SQL syntax. Allowed keywords are SELECT, WHERE, and SORTBY. Output is formatted as table.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><option>-f</option> or <option>--files</option></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>One or more DocBook XML or DC files.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><option>-g</option> or <option>--get</option></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Get key and returns value.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><option>-s</option> or <option>--set</option></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Set key=value property (one or more) to delete the key let the value blank.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
 </refsect1>
 <refsect1 id="docmanager.examples">
  <title>Examples</title>
  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><command>&progcmd;</command> -f example.xml -s hello=world</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Set the information value "world" in the property "hello".</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><command>&progcmd;</command> -f example.xml -g hello</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Reads the value of the property "hello". If you followed the first example, the output would be "hello=world".</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><command>&progcmd;</command> -f example.xml -a SELECT hello</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Shows the value of the property "hello". The output will be displayed as a table structure.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><command>&progcmd;</command> -f example.xml -a SELECT hello test</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>Shows the value of the property "hello" and "test". The output will be displayed as a table structure.</para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
 </refsect1>
</refentry>
